  "prompt": "In Bhagavad Gita 18th chapter, Lord Krishna says \"Arjuna is his dearest friend\". I am curious to know if there are any stories in Arjuna's previous birth, to become Lord's dearest friend in Vishnu's incarnation as Krishna?",
  "response": "In Hindu mythology, there are narratives that suggest connections between individuals across different lifetimes, reflecting the idea that relationships and roles can transcend multiple incarnations. The relationship between Lord Krishna and Arjuna is one such profound bond that has roots in their previous births.\n\nOne popular story is from the Mahabharata, which mentions that Arjuna was previously born as Nara, and Krishna as Narayana. Nara and Narayana are considered twin sages and incarnations of Vishnu who performed great penance and were inseparable companions. Their close friendship and divine partnership in their previous birth are often cited as a foundation for the deep bond they share in the Mahabharata.\n\nIn these narratives, the continuity of their friendship and divine mission across lifetimes emphasizes the eternal nature of their relationship and the idea that their roles as companions and divine agents are part of a larger cosmic plan. This background enriches the understanding of why Krishna refers to Arjuna as his dearest friend in the Bhagavad Gita, highlighting the depth of their connection and the spiritual significance of their roles.\n\nIt is important to note that interpretations and stories can vary, and different sources may provide additional or alternate details about their previous incarnations. However, the story of Nara-Narayana is one of the most commonly referenced connections in Hindu mythology.",
